          "body": "Verse 19b is the chapter's theological hinge: 'they could not drive out the inhabitants of the valley because they had iron chariots.' This is the first explicit explanation for an incomplete conquest, and it demands careful reading. Iron chariots were the military technology of the Late Bronze Age — the equivalent of armor-plated vehicles in the valleys where they could maneuver. But the narrator's theological point is not that God's power was insufficient. The same LORD who 'gave' the Canaanites into Judah's hand at Bezek (v.4) is 'with Judah' in the hill country (v.19a). The limitation is not divine but human — a failure of faith to trust the God of the hill country to be equally God of the valley. Deborah and Barak will later demonstrate exactly this: at Kishon, God routed Sisera's iron-chariot army (4:15; 5:20-21). The iron chariot of Judges 1:19 is not an explanation; it is an excuse. Every generation has its version of iron chariots — the obstacle that seems to justify stopping short of complete obedience."
